					<marginalia_text>
						Oeconomia biblica: et Eudromia aphoristica.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eudromus"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="Oeconomia" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="aphoristica" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Biblical economy, and Eudromian aphorisms.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						Expeditissimus Eudromi Cursus in familiari
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eudromus"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						bibliotheca[e] Oeconomia,
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="bibliotheca[e] Oeconomia" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						ad pra[e]sentem semper vsum: et summa proficiendi
						facultas,
						in analyse maximorum capitum aphoristica: cum
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="in analyse" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="aphoristica" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						flagranti Praxi; quanta esse potest pra[e]gnantiss[im]a.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="flagranti Praxi" type="straight"/>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="esse potest" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The most expedient course of Eudromus in the familiar arrangement of the library is
				always ready for present use. And he has the highest ability in carrying out aphorisms 
				in an analysis of the greatest topics with a passionate praxis,
				which is as pregnant as possible. <!-- CG: This is a strange sentence, unsure how "praxi" can be "flagranti." And what to do with the last clause? --> <!--Don't get this either, will ask specialist-->
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Quotidiè Legendum, audiendum, docendum, exercendum.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="pen" text="Quotidiè Legendum, audiendum, docendum, exercendum." type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Daily you must read, listen, teach, and exercise.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Conducit omnium Librorum Oeconomia promptissima: sed
						maximè prodest potentissimoru[m] Capitu[m] aphoristica
						synopsis; nuda, et stricta ad rem.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A most ready arrangement of all books is advantageous,
				but especially useful is an aphoristic summary of the most important topics,
				bare and straight to the point.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Argenti viui globus semper viuidissimus.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				A globe always most vivid with living silver.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Spirituista.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Spirituist.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Homo duplex, Platoni in Rep[ublica]: semivir.
						Verum est in propria Praxi: non in Comuni
						artium apparatu.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Plato"/>
					<book title="The Republic"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				In Plato's Republic, man is double, a half-man.
				The truth is found in one's own practice, not in the common material of the arts.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
